/* CISM :: content/pbqs.js — CISM performance-based question database (30). */
window.CISM = window.CISM || {}; CISM.pbqs = CISM.pbqs || [];
CISM.pbqs.push.apply(CISM.pbqs, [
{"id":"PBQ-01","format":1,"domain":1,"obj":"1A3","title":"Choosing the security governance structure","brief":"The board has asked how information security decisions should be organized now that the company has grown past its startup phase.","exhibitTitle":"WORKPAPER — GOVERNANCE STRUCTURE PROPOSAL","exhibit":"<span class='cy'>CURRENT STATE:</span> CISO reports to the CIO; security\n  priorities are routinely deprioritized behind delivery deadlines.\n<span class='cy'>PROPOSAL A:</span> CISO reports to the Chief Risk Officer; a\n  cross-functional steering committee reviews strategy quarterly.\n<span class='cy'>PROPOSAL B:</span> Keep CISO under CIO; add a security architect role.\n<span class='dim'>Note: board wants assurance security is not subordinated to delivery speed.</span>","fields":[{"label":"Which reporting change BEST addresses the board's concern?","hint":"Independence from delivery pressure","options":["Move the CISO to report to the CIO permanently for closer technical alignment","Move the CISO to report outside IT delivery, such as to the CRO or CEO","Leave reporting unchanged and add more security staff under the CIO"],"answer":1,"explain":"Reporting outside the IT delivery chain, such as to the CRO or CEO, removes the conflict of interest between delivery speed and risk oversight, which is exactly the board's concern. 'Move the CISO to report to the CIO permanently' preserves the exact conflict of interest the board flagged. 'Leave reporting unchanged and add more security staff' adds headcount without resolving the structural subordination of security to delivery."},{"label":"What is the primary purpose of the cross-functional steering committee in Proposal A?","hint":"Shared, business-wide decision-making","options":["To let the CISO make unilateral risk-acceptance decisions faster","To arbitrate competing priorities and make cross-departmental security decisions collectively","To replace the board's oversight responsibility entirely"],"answer":1,"explain":"A steering committee exists so that decisions affecting the whole business, such as risk acceptance for a risky initiative, are made collectively by representatives of the business rather than unilaterally by security. 'Let the CISO make unilateral risk-acceptance decisions faster' contradicts the collective, cross-functional purpose of the committee. 'Replace the board's oversight responsibility entirely' is wrong because the committee supports and feeds the board, it does not supplant board accountability."},{"label":"Who should retain ultimate accountability for the organization's information security risk after this change?","hint":"Accountability cannot be delegated away","options":["The board of directors","The CISO","The security steering committee"],"answer":0,"explain":"The board of directors holds ultimate accountability for enterprise risk, including information security risk, regardless of reporting lines or committees. 'The CISO' is accountable for designing and running the program, but that is a management accountability delegated by the board, not the ultimate one. 'The security steering committee' is a decision and arbitration forum, not the body holding ultimate enterprise accountability."}]},
{"id":"PBQ-02","format":1,"domain":1,"obj":"1B2","title":"Aligning the security strategy with the business","brief":"A new information security strategy has been drafted, and you must confirm it is properly aligned before it goes to the steering committee.","exhibitTitle":"WORKPAPER — STRATEGY DRAFT REVIEW","exhibit":"<span class='cy'>BUSINESS OBJECTIVE:</span> Expand into a new regulated market\n  within 12 months.\n<span class='cy'>DRAFT STRATEGY GOAL:</span> \"Deploy the newest intrusion\n  detection technology across all data centers.\"\n<span class='dim'>Note: draft strategy does not mention the new market, its\n  regulatory requirements, or a timeline tied to the expansion.</span>","fields":[{"label":"What is the core weakness in the draft strategy?","hint":"Strategy should derive from business goals","options":["It selects a technology-driven goal disconnected from the stated business objective","It is too vague to be measured","It has no budget line item attached"],"answer":0,"explain":"An information security strategy must derive from and support business objectives; a technology purchase unconnected to the market-expansion goal and its regulatory drivers fails that alignment test. 'It is too vague to be measured' is not the core issue here since the goal is concrete, it is simply pointed at the wrong target. 'It has no budget line item attached' is a planning detail, not the fundamental alignment failure the scenario highlights."},{"label":"What should the revised strategy goal directly reference?","hint":"Tie security work to the business driver","options":["The vendor's product roadmap for the intrusion detection system","The new market's regulatory requirements and the 12-month expansion timeline","Industry benchmarking data on detection technology adoption"],"answer":1,"explain":"Because the business objective is market expansion into a regulated market on a 12-month timeline, the strategy must explicitly address the regulatory requirements and that timeline to be aligned. 'The vendor's product roadmap' centers the strategy on a supplier's plans rather than the business driver. 'Industry benchmarking data on detection technology adoption' is useful context but does not connect the strategy to this specific business objective."},{"label":"Who should validate that the revised strategy is properly aligned before final approval?","hint":"Cross-functional business review","options":["The security steering committee, representing business and IT stakeholders","The intrusion detection vendor's solution architect","The security team alone, since they authored the strategy"],"answer":0,"explain":"The steering committee, made up of senior business, IT, legal, and security representatives, is the correct body to validate that a strategy serves enterprise objectives before approval. 'The intrusion detection vendor's solution architect' has a commercial interest and no visibility into the broader business strategy. 'The security team alone' authored the draft and lacks the independent, cross-functional perspective needed to catch the misalignment."}]},
{"id":"PBQ-03","format":1,"domain":1,"obj":"1A1","title":"Diagnosing a security culture failure","brief":"Phishing simulation click rates keep rising even though the same technical email filters remain in place and no policy has changed.","exhibitTitle":"WORKPAPER — SECURITY CULTURE SIGNAL","exhibit":"<span class='cy'>TREND:</span> Phishing click-rate up 40% over two quarters;\n  self-reported near-misses down 60% in the same period.\n<span class='cy'>CONTEXT:</span> Staff exit interviews mention \"security team\n  makes people feel stupid for reporting mistakes.\"\n<span class='dim'>Technical email filtering has not changed in 18 months.</span>","fields":[{"label":"What does the combination of rising clicks and falling self-reports most likely indicate?","hint":"Behavior, not technology, has shifted","options":["The email filtering technology has degraded and needs replacement","A cultural shift discouraging open reporting, not a technology failure","Employees have become less intelligent over time"],"answer":1,"explain":"Rising clicks paired with a sharp drop in self-reporting, alongside exit-interview comments about shame, points to a cultural breakdown in psychological safety around reporting, not a technical control failure. 'The email filtering technology has degraded' is contradicted by the stable filtering configuration noted in the exhibit. 'Employees have become less intelligent over time' is not a credible or supportable explanation for a behavioral trend."},{"label":"What is the BEST first action for the security manager to take?","hint":"Address the root behavioral cause","options":["Purchase a new email security gateway immediately","Investigate the reporting culture and adjust the team's tone and awareness approach","Discipline employees who click on simulated phishing emails"],"answer":1,"explain":"When a technically stable control is undermined by behavior, the best first step is to investigate and correct the underlying cultural cause, here the punitive tone discouraging reporting. 'Purchase a new email security gateway immediately' misdiagnoses a people problem as a technology gap. 'Discipline employees who click on simulated phishing emails' would deepen the exact fear culture that is already suppressing reporting."},{"label":"Which metric should the manager prioritize going forward to track whether the culture is improving?","hint":"Leading indicator of psychological safety","options":["Total number of marketing emails sent by the company","Self-reported near-miss and phishing-report rates","Number of firewall rules currently configured"],"answer":1,"explain":"Self-reported near-misses and phishing reports are leading indicators of a healthy, non-punitive reporting culture and directly track the problem identified. 'Total number of marketing emails sent by the company' is unrelated to security culture. 'Number of firewall rules currently configured' measures technical configuration, not behavior or culture."}]},
{"id":"PBQ-04","format":1,"domain":1,"obj":"1B4","title":"Building the business case for a security investment","brief":"You must justify a data loss prevention program to a finance-driven executive team that is skeptical of security spending.","exhibitTitle":"WORKPAPER — BUSINESS CASE DRAFT","exhibit":"<span class='cy'>PROPOSED PITCH A:</span> \"DLP is an industry best practice\n  and competitors already have it.\"\n<span class='cy'>PROPOSED PITCH B:</span> \"DLP reduces the likelihood and\n  impact of a data-exfiltration event that could halt our largest\n  client's contract renewal, tying cost to measurable business risk.\"\n<span class='dim'>Executive team's stated priority: protect recurring revenue.</span>","fields":[{"label":"Which pitch will resonate best with a finance-driven executive team?","hint":"Speak in business risk and value terms","options":["Pitch A, because keeping up with competitors is always persuasive","Pitch B, because it ties the investment to a measurable business risk and stated priority","Neither, because executives should trust the CISO's technical judgment without justification"],"answer":1,"explain":"Pitch B translates a technical control into business terms, revenue protection, which is precisely what a finance-driven executive team evaluates investments against. 'Pitch A' relies on competitor comparison and generic best-practice language, which rarely moves a skeptical, numbers-focused audience. 'Neither, because executives should trust the CISO's technical judgment' ignores that governance requires a business case and executive buy-in, not blind trust."},{"label":"What should the business case quantify to strengthen approval odds?","hint":"Executives fund what they can measure","options":["The number of security certifications held by the team","The estimated financial impact of the risk being mitigated versus the cost of the control","The number of vendors evaluated during procurement"],"answer":1,"explain":"A strong business case quantifies the cost of the risk against the cost of the control, giving executives a return-on-investment basis for the decision. 'The number of security certifications held by the team' speaks to staff credentials, not the financial case. 'The number of vendors evaluated during procurement' is a process detail that does not address whether the investment is worthwhile."},{"label":"After approval, what should the security manager report to sustain executive support?","hint":"Demonstrate value delivered, not just activity","options":["Metrics showing the control's effect on the business risk it was funded to address","A list of every configuration change made to the tool","The number of hours the security team worked each week"],"answer":0,"explain":"Reporting metrics tied to the risk the investment was meant to reduce demonstrates value delivery and sustains executive confidence and future funding. 'A list of every configuration change made to the tool' is operational detail irrelevant to executives. 'The number of hours the security team worked each week' measures effort, not outcomes or business value."}]},
{"id":"PBQ-05","format":1,"domain":1,"obj":"1A4","title":"Resolving conflicting compliance obligations","brief":"Legal counsel flags that a new customer contract's data retention clause conflicts with a foreign privacy law's shorter retention limit.","exhibitTitle":"WORKPAPER — REQUIREMENT CONFLICT","exhibit":"<span class='cy'>CONTRACT CLAUSE:</span> Customer requires 7-year retention of\n  transaction logs for its own audit purposes.\n<span class='cy'>PRIVACY LAW:</span> Foreign jurisdiction mandates deletion of\n  personal data within 2 years absent an exemption.\n<span class='dim'>Note: transaction logs contain personal data of foreign\n  data subjects.</span>","fields":[{"label":"What is the security manager's BEST first step when requirements conflict like this?","hint":"Don't unilaterally pick a side","options":["Silently follow whichever requirement was received most recently","Engage legal counsel to determine which obligation governs and document the resolution","Ignore the privacy law since the contract was signed by the business"],"answer":1,"explain":"Conflicting legal and contractual obligations should be resolved with legal counsel, who can determine precedence, applicable exemptions, and how to document the resolution for governance purposes. 'Silently follow whichever requirement was received most recently' is arbitrary and ignores legal analysis entirely. 'Ignore the privacy law since the contract was signed by the business' risks statutory noncompliance and penalties; a contract cannot override a legal retention mandate."},{"label":"Where should this obligation conflict and its resolution be documented?","hint":"Feed it into governance visibility","options":["In a private email between the CISO and the customer's account manager","In the compliance framework mapping obligations to systems, data, and controls, visible to governance","Nowhere, since it will resolve itself over time"],"answer":1,"explain":"A compliance framework that maps obligations to systems and controls is the governance artifact meant to capture exactly this kind of conflict and its resolution, keeping it visible to the steering committee and board. 'In a private email between the CISO and the customer's account manager' buries a compliance risk outside governance visibility. 'Nowhere, since it will resolve itself over time' abandons the due diligence the security manager is responsible for."},{"label":"If the privacy law includes no exemption, what should ultimately govern the retention period for that data?","hint":"Statutory law generally prevails over private contract","options":["The customer contract's 7-year term, because the customer is paying for the service","The privacy law's 2-year limit, since a contract cannot compel a statutory violation","Whichever period the security team finds easiest to implement technically"],"answer":1,"explain":"A contract cannot lawfully require retention that violates a binding statutory privacy obligation, so absent an exemption the shorter statutory limit governs. 'The customer contract's 7-year term, because the customer is paying' would knowingly commit a legal violation to satisfy a paying customer. 'Whichever period the security team finds easiest to implement technically' substitutes convenience for legal compliance, which is not a valid basis for the decision."}]},
{"id":"PBQ-06","format":1,"domain":1,"obj":"1B1","title":"Selecting a governance framework","brief":"The organization has no formal control framework and the steering committee wants a foundation that ties IT governance to enterprise objectives.","exhibitTitle":"WORKPAPER — FRAMEWORK SHORTLIST","exhibit":"<span class='cy'>OPTION 1:</span> COBIT — governance and management objectives\n  tying IT to enterprise goals (EDM and PBRM structure).\n<span class='cy'>OPTION 2:</span> A single product vendor's proprietary\n  configuration checklist.\n<span class='cy'>OPTION 3:</span> No framework; rely on ad hoc staff judgment.\n<span class='dim'>Steering committee goal: enterprise-wide governance\n  alignment, not just technical configuration.</span>","fields":[{"label":"Which option BEST meets the steering committee's stated goal?","hint":"Enterprise governance, not product-level checklists","options":["Option 1 (COBIT)","Option 2 (vendor checklist)","Option 3 (ad hoc judgment)"],"answer":0,"explain":"COBIT is designed specifically to connect enterprise governance objectives to IT management practices through its EDM and PBRM structure, matching the committee's goal. 'Option 2 (vendor checklist)' addresses configuration of a single product, not enterprise governance alignment. 'Option 3 (ad hoc judgment)' provides no consistent structure and cannot demonstrate governance to the board."},{"label":"Under a COBIT-based structure, who should set risk appetite?","hint":"Governance, not management","options":["The board or executive leadership through the governance (EDM) layer","Individual system administrators as they configure servers","The framework vendor's support desk"],"answer":0,"explain":"Setting risk appetite is a governance activity under the Evaluate-Direct-Monitor model, owned by the board or executive leadership, not by operational staff. 'Individual system administrators' operate within PBRM management activities and do not set enterprise risk appetite. 'The framework vendor's support desk' has no governance role in the organization at all."},{"label":"Once adopted, what should the security manager avoid doing with the framework?","hint":"Frameworks are tailored, not applied blindly","options":["Tailoring it to the organization's size, risk appetite, and industry context","Implementing every control objective verbatim regardless of relevance or cost","Mapping it to existing policies to identify gaps"],"answer":1,"explain":"Frameworks like COBIT are meant to be tailored to the organization's context; implementing every objective verbatim regardless of relevance wastes resources and can create controls disconnected from actual risk. 'Tailoring it to the organization's size, risk appetite, and industry context' is the correct, expected practice, not something to avoid. 'Mapping it to existing policies to identify gaps' is a sound gap-analysis step, also not something to avoid."}]},
{"id":"PBQ-07","format":2,"domain":2,"obj":"2A2","title":"Classifying risk treatment options","brief":"You must match each proposed action against the correct risk treatment strategy for the annual risk register review.","exhibitTitle":"WORKPAPER — RISK TREATMENT DECISIONS","exhibit":"<span class='cy'>R1:</span> Purchase cyber insurance to cover breach costs above\n  a set threshold.\n<span class='cy'>R2:</span> Discontinue an unprofitable product line that was the\n  sole reason a legacy, unpatchable system stayed online.\n<span class='cy'>R3:</span> Deploy multi-factor authentication on all remote\n  access to reduce the chance of account compromise.\n<span class='cy'>R4:</span> Formally sign off that a low-impact, low-likelihood\n  risk will not be treated further.","fields":[{"label":"Which risk treatment does R1 represent?","hint":"Shifting financial impact to a third party","options":["Risk transfer","Risk avoidance","Risk mitigation"],"answer":0,"explain":"Purchasing insurance shifts the financial impact of a loss to a third party, which is risk transfer, matching R1. 'Risk avoidance' would mean eliminating the activity causing the risk entirely, not insuring against it. 'Risk mitigation' reduces likelihood or impact directly through controls, which insurance does not do."},{"label":"Which risk treatment does R2 represent?","hint":"Eliminating the risk-bearing activity entirely","options":["Risk acceptance","Risk avoidance","Risk transfer"],"answer":1,"explain":"Discontinuing the product line removes the activity that required the legacy system, eliminating the risk entirely, which is risk avoidance, matching R2. 'Risk acceptance' would mean keeping the exposure and doing nothing further, not eliminating it. 'Risk transfer' shifts impact to a third party, which discontinuing an activity does not do."},{"label":"Which risk treatment does R4 represent?","hint":"Formal decision to leave the risk as is","options":["Risk mitigation","Risk acceptance","Risk avoidance"],"answer":1,"explain":"A formal, documented sign-off to leave a low-impact, low-likelihood risk untreated is risk acceptance, matching R4. 'Risk mitigation' implies applying controls to reduce it, which is explicitly not happening here. 'Risk avoidance' implies eliminating the underlying activity, which R4 does not describe."}]},
{"id":"PBQ-08","format":2,"domain":2,"obj":"2A5","title":"Matching qualitative risk ratings to scenarios","brief":"You must assign the correct likelihood and impact rating to each risk scenario for the heat map used in the risk register.","exhibitTitle":"WORKPAPER — RISK SCENARIOS FOR RATING","exhibit":"<span class='cy'>S1:</span> An internet-facing server with a known, unpatched\n  critical vulnerability and public exploit code available.\n<span class='cy'>S2:</span> A rarely used internal reporting tool with no\n  internet exposure and no sensitive data, missing a minor patch.\n<span class='cy'>S3:</span> A core payment processing system with strong controls\n  but whose compromise would halt all revenue collection.","fields":[{"label":"How should S1 be rated on likelihood?","hint":"Known exploit, public exposure","options":["High likelihood","Low likelihood","Likelihood is irrelevant to internet-facing systems"],"answer":0,"explain":"A known critical vulnerability with public exploit code on an internet-facing system is highly likely to be exploited, so S1 rates high likelihood. 'Low likelihood' contradicts the presence of a public exploit against an exposed system. 'Likelihood is irrelevant to internet-facing systems' is false; likelihood is always assessed regardless of exposure."},{"label":"How should S2 be rated overall compared to S1?","hint":"Low exposure, low data sensitivity, minor gap","options":["Higher overall risk than S1","Lower overall risk than S1","Identical risk to S1 because both have unpatched issues"],"answer":1,"explain":"S2's lack of internet exposure, lack of sensitive data, and minor severity make its overall risk lower than S1's actively exploitable, internet-facing critical vulnerability. 'Higher overall risk than S1' ignores the vast difference in exposure and severity. 'Identical risk to S1' incorrectly treats all unpatched systems as equivalent regardless of exploitability or exposure."},{"label":"How should S3 be characterized despite its strong controls?","hint":"Impact can remain significant even with mitigation","options":["Zero risk, since strong controls eliminate all risk","Potentially low likelihood but high impact if compromised, because of the revenue dependency","Impact should be ignored since likelihood is low"],"answer":1,"explain":"Strong controls can reduce likelihood, but the business impact of a successful compromise, halting all revenue collection, remains high, so S3 should reflect low likelihood but high impact. 'Zero risk, since strong controls eliminate all risk' is wrong because no control set reduces risk to zero. 'Impact should be ignored since likelihood is low' misapplies risk analysis; both dimensions must be assessed and multiplied, not one dismissed."}]},
{"id":"PBQ-09","format":2,"domain":2,"obj":"2B3","title":"Prioritizing control deficiencies for remediation","brief":"An internal assessment found several control deficiencies, and you must sequence remediation based on residual risk.","exhibitTitle":"WORKPAPER — CONTROL DEFICIENCY LOG","exhibit":"<span class='cy'>DEF-1:</span> Terminated employees retain VPN access for up to\n  10 days after departure; affects all business units.\n<span class='cy'>DEF-2:</span> A conference-room display lacks a password lock\n  screen; no sensitive data ever shown on it.\n<span class='cy'>DEF-3:</span> Database backups are unencrypted and stored\n  off-site at a third-party facility.","fields":[{"label":"Which deficiency should be remediated with the highest priority?","hint":"Weigh scope and exposure of sensitive data","options":["DEF-2 (display lock screen)","DEF-1 (delayed access revocation) or DEF-3 (unencrypted off-site backups), whichever carries higher residual risk after analysis","Remediate alphabetically by deficiency ID"],"answer":1,"explain":"DEF-1 and DEF-3 both involve broad exposure of sensitive access or data, so prioritization must come from analyzing which carries the higher residual risk, not a fixed rule; this keeps the decision risk-based. 'DEF-2 (display lock screen)' explicitly involves no sensitive data and is the lowest-impact item. 'Remediate alphabetically by deficiency ID' ignores risk entirely, which contradicts a risk-based remediation approach."},{"label":"Why does DEF-1 warrant serious concern despite being 'just' an access delay?","hint":"Terminated staff should lose access immediately","options":["Because a departed employee retaining access for days creates an unauthorized access window across the whole organization","Because VPN licensing costs increase with more active accounts","Because it violates a purely aesthetic naming convention"],"answer":0,"explain":"Delayed deprovisioning creates a real window in which a departed employee, who may be disgruntled or whose credentials may be compromised, retains unauthorized access across all business units. 'Because VPN licensing costs increase with more active accounts' is a minor cost concern, not the security risk driving prioritization. 'Because it violates a purely aesthetic naming convention' is nonsensical and irrelevant to risk."},{"label":"What makes DEF-3 a meaningful risk even though the backups are off-site?","hint":"Off-site storage does not equal protected","options":["Off-site storage automatically encrypts data in transit and at rest","Unencrypted backups at a third party are readable if the media or facility is compromised, regardless of location","Backups are never a target because attackers only care about production systems"],"answer":1,"explain":"Physical location does not protect data confidentiality; unencrypted backups can be read by anyone who accesses the media or facility, so the lack of encryption is the real exposure regardless of being off-site. 'Off-site storage automatically encrypts data' is factually wrong, location and encryption are independent. 'Backups are never a target' is false, backups are a well-known target for both theft and ransomware operations."}]},
{"id":"PBQ-10","format":2,"domain":2,"obj":"2A1","title":"Matching risk concepts to definitions","brief":"A new analyst has confused several core risk terms, and you must correctly match each term to its definition for a training exercise.","exhibitTitle":"WORKPAPER — RISK TERMINOLOGY MATCH","exhibit":"<span class='cy'>TERM 1:</span> The maximum amount of risk an organization is\n  willing to accept in pursuit of its objectives.\n<span class='cy'>TERM 2:</span> The acceptable deviation around that level\n  before management action is triggered.\n<span class='cy'>TERM 3:</span> The risk remaining after controls have been\n  applied.","fields":[{"label":"What term matches TERM 1?","hint":"The overall willingness to take on risk","options":["Risk appetite","Risk tolerance","Inherent risk"],"answer":0,"explain":"Risk appetite is the maximum level of risk an organization is willing to accept in pursuit of objectives, matching TERM 1. 'Risk tolerance' is the narrower, acceptable variation around that appetite, which is TERM 2, not TERM 1. 'Inherent risk' is the risk level before any controls are applied, a different concept entirely."},{"label":"What term matches TERM 2?","hint":"The acceptable band of deviation","options":["Risk tolerance","Risk appetite","Residual risk"],"answer":0,"explain":"Risk tolerance is the acceptable deviation around the risk appetite level before triggering management action, matching TERM 2. 'Risk appetite' is the broader overall willingness to accept risk, described in TERM 1. 'Residual risk' is what remains after controls, which is TERM 3, not TERM 2."},{"label":"What term matches TERM 3?","hint":"What's left after mitigation","options":["Inherent risk","Residual risk","Risk appetite"],"answer":1,"explain":"Residual risk is the risk that remains after controls have been applied, matching TERM 3 exactly. 'Inherent risk' is the risk level before controls are applied, the opposite point in the control lifecycle. 'Risk appetite' is an organizational willingness statement, not a post-control risk measurement."}]},
{"id":"PBQ-11","format":2,"domain":2,"obj":"2B5","title":"Selecting risk response owners","brief":"The risk register lists several risks pending a decision on who should own the response, and you must assign the correct accountable party.","exhibitTitle":"WORKPAPER — RISK OWNERSHIP ASSIGNMENT","exhibit":"<span class='cy'>RISK A:</span> A marketing database with customer PII has\n  outdated access permissions granting excess employees read access.\n<span class='cy'>RISK B:</span> A core banking application has an unpatched\n  vulnerability discovered by the vulnerability management team.\n<span class='cy'>RISK C:</span> A cloud storage vendor's security posture is\n  uncertain heading into contract renewal.","fields":[{"label":"Who should own the decision to accept or remediate RISK A?","hint":"Business accountability for the data","options":["The database administrator, since they manage the technical platform","The business data owner of the marketing database, who understands its value and impact","The vulnerability management team, since they found the issue"],"answer":1,"explain":"The business data owner is accountable for classifying data and accepting residual risk associated with it, because only the owner understands the business value and impact of exposure. 'The database administrator' is a custodian implementing technical safeguards, not the accountable decision-maker. 'The vulnerability management team' identifies and reports issues but does not own business risk-acceptance decisions."},{"label":"Who should drive remediation of RISK B in a core banking application?","hint":"Technical fix owned by the system's operational team, informed by risk","options":["The application or system owner, working with IT operations to patch on a risk-informed timeline","The marketing department, since they are unrelated and available","No one, since vulnerability management already logged it"],"answer":0,"explain":"The application or system owner, working with IT operations, is responsible for driving remediation on a timeline informed by the risk severity of the vulnerability. 'The marketing department' has no relationship to a core banking application and no relevant accountability. 'No one, since vulnerability management already logged it' confuses identification with remediation; logging a finding does not fix it."},{"label":"Who should evaluate RISK C before contract renewal?","hint":"Vendor risk spans procurement, security, and legal","options":["The security function, working with procurement and legal as part of vendor risk management","Only the original salesperson who signed the initial contract","No one, since the vendor has been used for years without an incident"],"answer":0,"explain":"Evaluating a vendor's security posture before renewal is a vendor risk management activity requiring security, procurement, and legal collaboration to assess and, if needed, renegotiate terms. 'Only the original salesperson' lacks the security expertise and objectivity to assess risk. 'No one, since the vendor has been used for years without an incident' assumes past absence of incidents guarantees future safety, which is not a valid risk management basis."}]},
{"id":"PBQ-12","format":2,"domain":2,"obj":"2A6","title":"Matching emerging threats to appropriate risk responses","brief":"The threat landscape has shifted, and you must match each emerging risk trend to the most appropriate organizational response.","exhibitTitle":"WORKPAPER — EMERGING THREAT RESPONSE MAP","exhibit":"<span class='cy'>TREND 1:</span> A sharp rise in supply-chain attacks via\n  compromised software updates from trusted vendors.\n<span class='cy'>TREND 2:</span> Employees increasingly using unsanctioned\n  AI tools to process confidential documents.\n<span class='cy'>TREND 3:</span> Ransomware groups now exfiltrating data before\n  encrypting it, enabling double extortion.","fields":[{"label":"What response BEST addresses TREND 1?","hint":"Trust but verify the supply chain","options":["Strengthen third-party and software supply-chain risk assessment and integrity verification","Ignore vendor updates since they are pre-tested by the vendor","Ban all third-party software company-wide"],"answer":0,"explain":"Rising supply-chain compromise calls for stronger third-party risk assessment and verifying the integrity of vendor updates before deployment. 'Ignore vendor updates since they are pre-tested by the vendor' is precisely the blind trust that supply-chain attacks exploit. 'Ban all third-party software company-wide' is operationally unworkable and disproportionate to the actual risk."},{"label":"What response BEST addresses TREND 2?","hint":"Shadow IT and data governance for AI use","options":["Establish an acceptable-use policy for AI tools with approved options and data-handling rules","Allow unrestricted AI tool use since it improves productivity","Discipline any employee who has ever mentioned AI tools"],"answer":0,"explain":"An acceptable-use policy that channels employees toward approved, vetted AI tools with clear data-handling rules addresses the risk while still enabling productivity. 'Allow unrestricted AI tool use since it improves productivity' ignores the confidentiality risk of feeding sensitive data into unsanctioned tools. 'Discipline any employee who has ever mentioned AI tools' is punitive, disproportionate, and does not establish a sustainable governance control."},{"label":"What does the shift described in TREND 3 imply for incident response planning?","hint":"Encryption is no longer the only concern","options":["Response plans should also address data exfiltration and disclosure risk, not just system recovery","Response plans can ignore exfiltration since backups will restore encrypted data anyway","No planning change is needed since ransomware is still just ransomware"],"answer":0,"explain":"Double extortion means data is stolen before encryption, so incident response and communication plans must address exfiltration and potential public disclosure, not just restoring encrypted systems from backup. 'Response plans can ignore exfiltration since backups will restore encrypted data' misses that stolen data can still be leaked or sold even after systems are restored. 'No planning change is needed since ransomware is still just ransomware' fails to recognize that the double-extortion tactic fundamentally changes the impact and required response."}]},
{"id":"PBQ-13","format":3,"domain":3,"obj":"3A1","title":"Sequencing the security program development lifecycle","brief":"A newly hired information security manager must build the security program from the ground up and needs the activities placed in the correct order.","exhibitTitle":"WORKPAPER — PROGRAM BUILD-OUT STEPS","exhibit":"<span class='cy'>ACTIVITY LIST (unordered):</span>\n  X. Select and implement specific controls.\n  Y. Assess current state against the desired state defined\n     by the approved strategy.\n  Z. Obtain executive approval of the security strategy\n     and target risk posture.","fields":[{"label":"Which activity should occur FIRST?","hint":"Direction before assessment or execution","options":["X (select controls)","Y (assess current state)","Z (obtain strategy approval)"],"answer":2,"explain":"Executive approval of the strategy and target risk posture must come first, since it sets the direction everything else is measured against. 'X (select controls)' without an approved strategy risks building controls that do not serve the eventual direction. 'Y (assess current state)' needs the approved desired state as a baseline for comparison, so it cannot meaningfully precede strategy approval."},{"label":"Which activity logically follows strategy approval?","hint":"Know the gap before you close it","options":["Y (assess current state against the desired state)","X (select and implement controls)","Re-obtain executive approval a second time"],"answer":0,"explain":"After the strategy and target state are approved, the next step is a gap assessment comparing current state to that desired state, which is Y. 'X (select and implement controls)' before understanding the gap risks selecting the wrong or unnecessary controls. 'Re-obtain executive approval a second time' is redundant and does not belong in this sequence."},{"label":"Which activity should occur LAST in this sequence?","hint":"Execution follows direction and analysis","options":["Z (obtain strategy approval)","Y (assess current state)","X (select and implement controls)"],"answer":2,"explain":"Selecting and implementing specific controls, X, is the execution step that follows both an approved strategy and a completed gap assessment, so it comes last. 'Z (obtain strategy approval)' must occur first to set direction. 'Y (assess current state)' must occur second, after approval and before control selection, to correctly scope the gap."}]},
{"id":"PBQ-14","format":3,"domain":3,"obj":"3A4","title":"Selecting the security architecture approach","brief":"The enterprise architecture team is deciding how security requirements will be embedded into new system designs going forward.","exhibitTitle":"WORKPAPER — ARCHITECTURE APPROACH OPTIONS","exhibit":"<span class='cy'>OPTION 1:</span> Security requirements are defined during\n  initial design, alongside functional and performance requirements.\n<span class='cy'>OPTION 2:</span> Security requirements are added as a final\n  review gate just before production deployment.\n<span class='cy'>OPTION 3:</span> Security requirements are left to individual\n  developers' discretion.","fields":[{"label":"Which option reflects security-by-design?","hint":"Bake it in from the start","options":["Option 1","Option 2","Option 3"],"answer":0,"explain":"Security-by-design means security requirements are defined at the outset, alongside functional and performance requirements, which is Option 1. 'Option 2' bolts security on at the end, the opposite of security-by-design, and is far more costly to remediate. 'Option 3' provides no consistent requirement at all, leaving security to chance."},{"label":"What is the main risk of Option 2's approach?","hint":"Cost and feasibility of late-stage changes","options":["Findings at a late review gate are costly and difficult to remediate without delaying or reworking the release","Late reviews are always faster than early design work","There is no risk difference compared to Option 1"],"answer":0,"explain":"Discovering security gaps at a final gate, just before deployment, is expensive to fix and often forces a choice between delaying the release or shipping with known weaknesses. 'Late reviews are always faster than early design work' is false and is exactly why late-stage rework is costly. 'There is no risk difference compared to Option 1' ignores the well-established cost escalation of fixing issues later in the lifecycle."},{"label":"Why is Option 3 unacceptable from a governance perspective?","hint":"Consistency and accountability require defined requirements","options":["It produces inconsistent, unaccountable security outcomes across systems","It gives developers helpful flexibility with no downside","It is identical in effect to Option 1"],"answer":0,"explain":"Leaving security to individual discretion produces inconsistent outcomes with no defined baseline or accountability, undermining governance and audit ability. 'It gives developers helpful flexibility with no downside' ignores the resulting inconsistency and unmanaged risk. 'It is identical in effect to Option 1' is false, Option 1 defines requirements up front while Option 3 defines none."}]},
{"id":"PBQ-15","format":3,"domain":3,"obj":"3B7","title":"Evaluating security awareness program effectiveness","brief":"The security team wants to know whether its annual awareness training is actually working, not just being completed.","exhibitTitle":"WORKPAPER — AWARENESS PROGRAM METRICS","exhibit":"<span class='cy'>METRIC A:</span> 98% completion rate of the annual training module.\n<span class='cy'>METRIC B:</span> Phishing simulation click rate and time-to-report\n  trend across the year.\n<span class='cy'>METRIC C:</span> Number of training slides included in the module.","fields":[{"label":"Which metric BEST measures whether the program is changing behavior?","hint":"Behavior over completion","options":["Metric A (completion rate)","Metric B (click rate and time-to-report trend)","Metric C (slide count)"],"answer":1,"explain":"Click rate and time-to-report trends measure actual behavioral change in response to real-world-style phishing, which is what an effective program should produce. 'Metric A (completion rate)' only shows people clicked through the module, not that behavior changed. 'Metric C (slide count)' measures training content volume, not outcomes at all."},{"label":"What is the main limitation of relying solely on Metric A?","hint":"Completion is not the same as comprehension or behavior change","options":["It cannot distinguish between passive completion and genuine behavior change","It is too expensive to collect","It cannot be reported to the steering committee"],"answer":0,"explain":"A high completion rate only confirms people clicked through the training; it says nothing about whether they understood the content or changed their behavior. 'It is too expensive to collect' is false, completion tracking is typically automatic and low-cost. 'It cannot be reported to the steering committee' is also false, completion rates are commonly reported, they are simply insufficient alone."},{"label":"What should the security manager do if Metric B shows no improvement despite high Metric A completion?","hint":"Diagnose why training isn't translating into behavior","options":["Conclude the program is fully effective because completion is high","Investigate why training completion is not translating into behavior change and revise the approach","Cancel all awareness training since it clearly does not work"],"answer":1,"explain":"A gap between high completion and flat or worsening behavioral metrics signals that the training content, delivery, or reinforcement needs revision, not abandonment. 'Conclude the program is fully effective because completion is high' ignores the behavioral evidence showing otherwise. 'Cancel all awareness training since it clearly does not work' overreacts; the correct response is to diagnose and improve, not eliminate the program entirely."}]},
{"id":"PBQ-16","format":3,"domain":3,"obj":"3B2","title":"Prioritizing security program budget requests","brief":"The security program has more proposed initiatives than budget, and you must recommend which to fund first based on the business case.","exhibitTitle":"WORKPAPER — BUDGET REQUEST QUEUE","exhibit":"<span class='cy'>REQ-1:</span> Replace an aging control that protects the\n  organization's single highest-revenue application; current\n  control has known reliability failures.\n<span class='cy'>REQ-2:</span> Rebrand the internal security awareness portal\n  with a new visual theme.\n<span class='cy'>REQ-3:</span> Add a redundant control to a system that already\n  has three layered, effective controls and negligible risk.","fields":[{"label":"Which request should be funded FIRST?","hint":"Highest risk reduction to core business value","options":["REQ-1","REQ-2","REQ-3"],"answer":0,"explain":"REQ-1 addresses a known-unreliable control protecting the organization's highest-revenue application, representing the greatest risk reduction per dollar spent. 'REQ-2' is a cosmetic change with no measurable risk-reduction value. 'REQ-3' adds redundant protection to an already well-controlled, low-risk system, offering minimal marginal benefit."},{"label":"Why is REQ-3 a poor use of limited budget?","hint":"Diminishing returns on already-mitigated risk","options":["Because it adds negligible risk reduction given existing layered controls and low residual risk","Because redundant controls are illegal","Because the system in question is scheduled for decommissioning next week"],"answer":0,"explain":"When a system already has three effective, layered controls and negligible residual risk, adding another control yields very little additional risk reduction relative to its cost, a poor use of limited funds. 'Because redundant controls are illegal' is false, redundancy is a legitimate design choice, just not the best use of scarce budget here. 'Because the system in question is scheduled for decommissioning' is not stated in the scenario and is not the given reason."},{"label":"How should the security manager justify the prioritization decision to the steering committee?","hint":"Frame it in risk and business value terms","options":["By showing the risk-reduction value of REQ-1 relative to its cost, compared against the other requests","By stating that REQ-1 was submitted first chronologically","By flipping a coin between the requests to appear impartial"],"answer":0,"explain":"Presenting the risk-reduction value relative to cost, compared across the competing requests, gives the steering committee a defensible, risk-based rationale for the funding decision. 'By stating that REQ-1 was submitted first chronologically' is an arbitrary basis unrelated to risk or value. 'By flipping a coin' abandons any analytical basis and would not withstand governance scrutiny."}]},
{"id":"PBQ-17","format":3,"domain":3,"obj":"3B9","title":"Choosing the right third-party assurance mechanism","brief":"Procurement wants to onboard a new SaaS vendor that will process customer financial data, and you must recommend the right assurance approach.","exhibitTitle":"WORKPAPER — VENDOR ASSURANCE OPTIONS","exhibit":"<span class='cy'>OPTION A:</span> Accept the vendor's marketing page claiming\n  \"bank-grade security.\"\n<span class='cy'>OPTION B:</span> Request an independent SOC 2 Type II report\n  and review it against the intended use of the service.\n<span class='cy'>OPTION C:</span> Skip assurance since the contract includes a\n  liability clause.","fields":[{"label":"Which option provides the strongest, most defensible assurance?","hint":"Independent, evidence-based, and time-tested","options":["Option A","Option B","Option C"],"answer":1,"explain":"A SOC 2 Type II report is independently audited evidence of controls operating effectively over a period of time, making it the strongest and most defensible basis for vendor assurance. 'Option A' is unverified marketing language with no independent evidence behind it. 'Option C' relies on a legal remedy after the fact rather than assessing the risk before onboarding, which does not prevent a breach or its consequences."},{"label":"Why is Option A insufficient on its own?","hint":"Marketing claims are not independently verified","options":["Because it is an unverified, self-reported claim with no independent audit behind it","Because marketing claims are always legally binding","Because it costs more than a SOC 2 report"],"answer":0,"explain":"A vendor's own marketing claim is self-reported and unverified by any independent party, so it cannot substitute for objective assurance evidence. 'Because marketing claims are always legally binding' is false and, even if true, would not verify actual control effectiveness. 'Because it costs more than a SOC 2 report' is incorrect and irrelevant, marketing pages are typically free to review."},{"label":"What should the security manager do with the SOC 2 Type II report once received?","hint":"Reports must be evaluated, not just filed","options":["File it away unread to demonstrate due diligence was performed","Review it for scope, exceptions, and relevance to the specific service being used","Reject the vendor automatically because an audit was required at all"],"answer":1,"explain":"A SOC 2 report must be reviewed for its scope, any noted exceptions, and whether it actually covers the service and controls relevant to this engagement, not just collected as a checkbox artifact. 'File it away unread' provides no real assurance despite the appearance of due diligence. 'Reject the vendor automatically because an audit was required' misunderstands that requesting and reviewing such reports is a normal, expected part of vendor assurance."}]},
{"id":"PBQ-18","format":3,"domain":3,"obj":"3A7","title":"Designing security metrics for the program","brief":"The steering committee has asked for a small set of security program metrics that are meaningful to a non-technical audience.","exhibitTitle":"WORKPAPER — CANDIDATE METRICS","exhibit":"<span class='cy'>METRIC 1:</span> Mean time to detect and mean time to contain\n  security incidents, trended quarterly.\n<span class='cy'>METRIC 2:</span> Total number of firewall rules currently active.\n<span class='cy'>METRIC 3:</span> Percentage of critical systems patched within\n  the organization's defined SLA.","fields":[{"label":"Which metrics are MOST appropriate to present to the steering committee?","hint":"Business-relevant, trendable, outcome-oriented","options":["Metric 2 only, since it is the easiest to count","Metrics 1 and 3, since they show outcome trends relevant to risk and governance","All three metrics carry equal governance value"],"answer":1,"explain":"Detection/containment time and SLA-based patch compliance are outcome-oriented, trendable measures that map directly to risk exposure and are meaningful to a non-technical governance audience. 'Metric 2 only' is a raw technical count with no inherent meaning about risk or performance. 'All three metrics carry equal governance value' incorrectly elevates a low-context technical count to the same importance as outcome trends."},{"label":"Why is Metric 2 (firewall rule count) a weak governance metric on its own?","hint":"A count says nothing about effectiveness","options":["Because a rule count reveals nothing about whether the rules are effective, current, or properly configured","Because firewalls are being phased out industry-wide","Because the number can never change once set"],"answer":0,"explain":"A simple count of firewall rules says nothing about whether those rules are correctly configured, still necessary, or actually reducing risk, so it lacks meaningful governance value on its own. 'Because firewalls are being phased out industry-wide' is not a supported or relevant claim. 'Because the number can never change once set' is factually incorrect, rule counts change regularly."},{"label":"What should accompany Metric 1 and Metric 3 when presented to the committee?","hint":"Context makes metrics actionable","options":["Trend direction and context explaining what changes and why they matter to the business","Raw log files with no summary","Nothing further; numbers speak for themselves"],"answer":0,"explain":"Presenting trend direction and business context turns raw metrics into actionable governance information the committee can use to direct resources or ask informed questions. 'Raw log files with no summary' would overwhelm a non-technical audience without adding clarity. 'Nothing further; numbers speak for themselves' ignores that non-technical stakeholders need interpretation to act on metrics."}]},
{"id":"PBQ-19","format":3,"domain":3,"obj":"3B4","title":"Handling a failed control test during program assurance","brief":"A quarterly control self-assessment reveals that a key encryption control has not been operating as designed for several months.","exhibitTitle":"WORKPAPER — CONTROL TEST RESULT","exhibit":"<span class='cy'>CONTROL:</span> Encryption of data at rest for the customer\n  records database.\n<span class='cy'>TEST RESULT:</span> Encryption service silently failed 4\n  months ago after a configuration change; data has been stored\n  unencrypted since.\n<span class='dim'>Note: no breach has been detected or reported.</span>","fields":[{"label":"What is the security manager's FIRST priority upon discovering this?","hint":"Stop the ongoing exposure and assess scope","options":["Re-enable encryption going forward and assess the scope and impact of the historical exposure","Wait for the next scheduled assessment cycle to confirm the finding","Quietly note it in a personal file without escalating"],"answer":0,"explain":"The first priority is to stop the ongoing exposure by restoring encryption and to assess how much data was affected and for how long, which drives the rest of the response. 'Wait for the next scheduled assessment cycle' leaves the exposure ongoing and delays a necessary response. 'Quietly note it in a personal file without escalating' conceals a material control failure from governance and possibly from legal/compliance obligations."},{"label":"Who else must be informed given the multi-month duration of the failure?","hint":"Legal, compliance, and governance visibility","options":["No one, since no breach has been confirmed yet","Legal, compliance, and appropriate governance bodies, to assess notification and reporting obligations","Only the vendor who sold the encryption service"],"answer":1,"explain":"A multi-month control failure affecting customer records data must be escalated to legal, compliance, and governance so they can assess breach notification obligations and reporting requirements, even without confirmed exploitation. 'No one, since no breach has been confirmed yet' ignores that unencrypted storage of customer data for months is itself a reportable control failure in many regulatory regimes. 'Only the vendor who sold the encryption service' misses the internal governance and legal obligations entirely."},{"label":"What should be added to prevent a silent failure like this from persisting undetected in the future?","hint":"Continuous control monitoring","options":["Automated, continuous monitoring and alerting on the control's operating status","Increasing the interval between control self-assessments","Removing the control entirely since it failed once"],"answer":0,"explain":"Automated, continuous monitoring with alerting would have caught the silent failure within hours or days rather than months, closing the detection gap. 'Increasing the interval between control self-assessments' would make silent failures persist even longer before detection. 'Removing the control entirely since it failed once' eliminates a needed protection instead of fixing the monitoring gap that allowed the failure to go unnoticed."}]},
{"id":"PBQ-20","format":3,"domain":3,"obj":"3A9","title":"Integrating security into the SDLC","brief":"A development team wants to skip security testing to hit an aggressive release date for a customer-facing application.","exhibitTitle":"WORKPAPER — RELEASE REQUEST","exhibit":"<span class='cy'>REQUEST:</span> Development lead asks to skip the scheduled\n  static and dynamic application security testing to hit Friday's\n  release date.\n<span class='cy'>CONTEXT:</span> Application processes customer payment data;\n  no prior security testing has been performed on this release.\n<span class='dim'>Business sponsor has publicly committed to the Friday date.</span>","fields":[{"label":"What is the security manager's BEST response to this request?","hint":"Risk-based, not rubber-stamped","options":["Approve the skip immediately to support the business commitment","Explain the risk of releasing untested code handling payment data and propose risk-informed options, such as expedited testing or a documented, time-boxed risk acceptance by the appropriate owner","Refuse to discuss the matter and let the release date slip silently"],"answer":1,"explain":"The security manager should surface the real risk of shipping untested payment-processing code and offer constructive, risk-based options, such as expedited testing or an explicit, owner-approved risk acceptance, preserving both business awareness and governance integrity. 'Approve the skip immediately' bypasses required assurance on a high-risk, payment-related release without any risk analysis. 'Refuse to discuss the matter and let the release date slip silently' fails to engage constructively or offer the business any informed choice."},{"label":"If a time-boxed risk acceptance is chosen, who should approve it?","hint":"Business risk owner, not security alone","options":["The development lead who requested the skip","The appropriate business risk owner or governance body with authority to accept that level of risk","No one; the security manager can approve it unilaterally to save time"],"answer":1,"explain":"Accepting a risk on the business's behalf, especially one touching payment data, requires the appropriate business risk owner or governance body with actual authority, not the party requesting the shortcut. 'The development lead who requested the skip' has a conflict of interest and no risk-acceptance authority. 'No one; the security manager can approve it unilaterally' oversteps the security manager's role, which is to advise and facilitate, not unilaterally accept business risk."},{"label":"What should be documented regardless of the outcome?","hint":"Governance requires a paper trail","options":["The risk identified, the decision made, who made it, and any compensating actions or timeline for remediation","Nothing; verbal agreement is sufficient","Only the development lead's original request, with no further detail"],"answer":0,"explain":"Documenting the identified risk, the decision, the responsible approver, and any compensating controls or remediation timeline creates an auditable record and reinforces accountability. 'Nothing; verbal agreement is sufficient' leaves no evidence of due diligence if the risk materializes. 'Only the development lead's original request' omits the decision and accountability trail that governance requires."}]},
{"id":"PBQ-21","format":3,"domain":3,"obj":"3B11","title":"Measuring return on security investment for the program","brief":"The CFO has asked the security manager to demonstrate the value delivered by the security program over the past year in terms the finance team will accept.","exhibitTitle":"WORKPAPER — VALUE REPORTING OPTIONS","exhibit":"<span class='cy'>OPTION 1:</span> Report the number of security tools purchased.\n<span class='cy'>OPTION 2:</span> Report estimated loss avoidance from incidents\n  prevented or contained early, alongside compliance posture and\n  audit findings trend.\n<span class='cy'>OPTION 3:</span> Report how many hours the security team worked.","fields":[{"label":"Which option BEST communicates value in terms finance will accept?","hint":"Speak in risk-adjusted financial and compliance terms","options":["Option 1","Option 2","Option 3"],"answer":1,"explain":"Estimated loss avoidance, compliance posture, and audit findings trends translate security activity into financial and governance terms a CFO can evaluate against investment. 'Option 1' counts purchases, which says nothing about value or risk reduction. 'Option 3' measures effort, not outcomes, and does not speak to financial value at all."},{"label":"What is a key caveat the security manager should state when presenting loss-avoidance estimates?","hint":"Estimates are not precise financial facts","options":["That the figures are estimates based on reasonable assumptions, not precise, guaranteed savings","That the figures are guaranteed and audited to the same standard as financial statements","That loss avoidance cannot be estimated at all, so no figure should ever be given"],"answer":0,"explain":"Loss-avoidance figures are necessarily estimates built on reasonable assumptions about prevented impact, and presenting them honestly as such preserves credibility with a finance audience. 'That the figures are guaranteed and audited to the same standard as financial statements' overstates precision and could mislead the CFO. 'That loss avoidance cannot be estimated at all' is overly conservative and would leave the security program unable to demonstrate value in financial terms at all."},{"label":"How should this reporting approach evolve over time?","hint":"Consistency enables trend analysis","options":["Report different, unrelated metrics each year to keep things interesting","Maintain consistent metrics year over year so the CFO can track trends and validate program value over time","Stop reporting once the CFO approves one year's budget"],"answer":1,"explain":"Using consistent metrics year over year allows the CFO and steering committee to track trends, validate that the program continues to deliver value, and make informed future investment decisions. 'Report different, unrelated metrics each year' destroys comparability and undermines trend analysis. 'Stop reporting once the CFO approves one year's budget' abandons the ongoing governance relationship and risks losing future support."}]},
{"id":"PBQ-22","format":4,"domain":4,"obj":"4A2","title":"Classifying the incident severity level","brief":"The security operations center has escalated three concurrent events, and you must assign each the correct severity for response prioritization.","exhibitTitle":"WORKPAPER — CONCURRENT EVENT TRIAGE","exhibit":"<span class='cy'>EVENT A:</span> Ransomware actively encrypting file shares\n  across three regional offices; business operations halted.\n<span class='cy'>EVENT B:</span> A single employee's laptop flagged for an\n  outdated antivirus signature; no malicious activity observed.\n<span class='cy'>EVENT C:</span> A phishing email reported by one employee who\n  did not click any link or open any attachment.","fields":[{"label":"How should EVENT A be classified?","hint":"Active, spreading, business-halting","options":["Critical/high severity, requiring immediate incident response activation","Low severity, to be reviewed at the next weekly meeting","Not an incident, since it is only affecting file shares"],"answer":0,"explain":"Active ransomware spreading across multiple offices and halting operations meets the definition of a critical, high-severity incident requiring immediate response activation. 'Low severity, to be reviewed at the next weekly meeting' would allow the ransomware to keep spreading unchecked, which is unacceptable given the active business impact. 'Not an incident, since it is only affecting file shares' understates the situation; halted operations from active ransomware is unambiguously a major incident."},{"label":"How should EVENT B be classified relative to EVENT A?","hint":"No malicious activity confirmed, isolated scope","options":["The same critical severity as EVENT A","Much lower severity, handled as routine vulnerability/patch management","Higher severity than EVENT A because antivirus is involved"],"answer":1,"explain":"A single outdated signature with no observed malicious activity is a routine patch/configuration issue, appropriately handled as low-severity operational work rather than an active incident. 'The same critical severity as EVENT A' wildly overstates a non-malicious, isolated finding. 'Higher severity than EVENT A' is unsupported since there is no active compromise, spread, or business impact involved."},{"label":"What is the appropriate handling for EVENT C?","hint":"Reported but no compromise occurred","options":["Treat as a confirmed breach requiring board notification","Log and analyze the reported phishing email, but treat it as low severity since no interaction occurred","Ignore it since nothing happened"],"answer":1,"explain":"A reported phishing email with no click or attachment interaction should still be logged and analyzed, for example to block the sender or identify a broader campaign, but it is low severity since no compromise occurred. 'Treat as a confirmed breach requiring board notification' vastly overstates an event where no interaction took place. 'Ignore it since nothing happened' wastes valuable threat intelligence and discourages the very reporting behavior the organization wants to encourage."}]},
{"id":"PBQ-23","format":4,"domain":4,"obj":"4A5","title":"Sequencing the incident response lifecycle","brief":"A confirmed data breach is underway, and the response team needs the phases performed in the correct order.","exhibitTitle":"WORKPAPER — IR LIFECYCLE PHASES","exhibit":"<span class='cy'>PHASES (unordered):</span>\n  P1. Eradication — remove the root cause.\n  P2. Detection and analysis — confirm and scope the incident.\n  P3. Containment — stop further spread or damage.\n  P4. Recovery — restore normal operations.\n  P5. Post-incident (lessons learned) review.","fields":[{"label":"Which phase comes FIRST?","hint":"You cannot respond to what you haven't confirmed","options":["P3 (containment)","P2 (detection and analysis)","P5 (lessons learned)"],"answer":1,"explain":"Detection and analysis must occur first to confirm an incident is actually happening and understand its scope before any response action is taken. 'P3 (containment)' cannot be effectively targeted until the scope is understood through detection and analysis. 'P5 (lessons learned)' is the final phase, reviewing the response after it concludes, not the starting point."},{"label":"Which phase should immediately follow containment?","hint":"Remove the cause before restoring service","options":["P1 (eradication)","P4 (recovery)","P5 (lessons learned)"],"answer":0,"explain":"After containment stops the spread, eradication removes the root cause, such as malware or an exploited vulnerability, before systems are restored. 'P4 (recovery)' before eradication risks restoring systems that are still compromised or reinfectable. 'P5 (lessons learned)' is the final review phase and does not belong between containment and recovery."},{"label":"Which phase comes LAST, and what is its purpose?","hint":"Improve the process going forward","options":["P4 (recovery), to make sure systems are back online quickly","P5 (lessons learned), to identify process improvements and update the incident response plan","P2 (detection and analysis), repeated at the very end to confirm nothing was missed"],"answer":1,"explain":"Lessons learned occurs last, capturing what worked, what did not, and updating the incident response plan and controls accordingly. 'P4 (recovery)' occurs before the final review, not after it, since operations must be restored before the retrospective. 'P2 (detection and analysis), repeated at the very end' misplaces a phase that occurs at the start of the response, not as a closing activity."}]},
{"id":"PBQ-24","format":4,"domain":4,"obj":"4B3","title":"Deciding on breach notification obligations","brief":"A confirmed breach exposed personal data of customers in two jurisdictions with different notification laws, and legal needs a recommendation on next steps.","exhibitTitle":"WORKPAPER — BREACH NOTIFICATION FACTS","exhibit":"<span class='cy'>JURISDICTION 1:</span> Requires notification to the regulator\n  within 72 hours of becoming aware of a personal data breach.\n<span class='cy'>JURISDICTION 2:</span> Requires notification only if a\n  documented risk assessment shows a likelihood of harm.\n<span class='cy'>STATUS:</span> Breach confirmed 6 hours ago; risk assessment\n  for Jurisdiction 2 not yet complete.","fields":[{"label":"What is the correct action regarding Jurisdiction 1's requirement?","hint":"The clock is already running","options":["Begin preparing the mandatory 72-hour notification process immediately, since the clock started at confirmation","Wait until the Jurisdiction 2 risk assessment is complete before taking any action","Assume Jurisdiction 1 does not apply since the breach was only just confirmed"],"answer":0,"explain":"Since Jurisdiction 1 mandates notification within 72 hours of becoming aware, and the breach was confirmed 6 hours ago, the notification process must begin immediately to meet that fixed deadline. 'Wait until the Jurisdiction 2 risk assessment is complete' risks missing Jurisdiction 1's independent, time-bound requirement. 'Assume Jurisdiction 1 does not apply since the breach was only just confirmed' misunderstands that the 72-hour clock starts at the moment of confirmation, not at some later point."},{"label":"What must happen before determining Jurisdiction 2's notification obligation?","hint":"Assessment-triggered requirement","options":["Nothing further; notify immediately regardless of harm likelihood","Complete the documented risk assessment evaluating the likelihood of harm to affected individuals","Wait for Jurisdiction 1's regulator to decide on behalf of both jurisdictions"],"answer":1,"explain":"Jurisdiction 2's requirement is conditioned on a documented risk assessment of harm likelihood, so that assessment must be completed to determine whether notification is triggered there. 'Nothing further; notify immediately regardless of harm likelihood' ignores the jurisdiction's actual legal trigger. 'Wait for Jurisdiction 1's regulator to decide on behalf of both jurisdictions' incorrectly assumes one regulator's process governs an unrelated jurisdiction's separate legal requirement."},{"label":"Who should be coordinating this multi-jurisdiction notification decision?","hint":"Cross-functional, not security alone","options":["The security incident response lead working with legal counsel and privacy/compliance functions","The security manager alone, without legal input, to move faster","The affected customers, who should decide whether they want to be notified"],"answer":0,"explain":"Multi-jurisdiction breach notification decisions require the incident response lead to coordinate closely with legal counsel and privacy/compliance, since the obligations are legal and jurisdiction-specific. 'The security manager alone, without legal input' risks a legally incorrect or incomplete notification decision. 'The affected customers, who should decide whether they want to be notified' misunderstands that notification is a legal obligation, not a customer preference."}]},
{"id":"PBQ-25","format":4,"domain":4,"obj":"4A7","title":"Preserving evidence during an active incident","brief":"Responders are working a suspected insider data theft case, and evidence handling decisions must hold up if the matter goes to legal action.","exhibitTitle":"WORKPAPER — EVIDENCE HANDLING DECISION","exhibit":"<span class='cy'>SITUATION:</span> Suspect's workstation is still powered on and\n  logged in; a responder wants to start reviewing files immediately\n  by opening them directly on the live system.\n<span class='cy'>ALTERNATIVE:</span> Forensic imaging tool and documented\n  chain-of-custody procedure are available but take 30 minutes to set up.","fields":[{"label":"What is the BEST course of action?","hint":"Preserve integrity before analysis","options":["Open files directly on the live system immediately to save time","Use the forensic imaging tool to create a verified copy under documented chain of custody before analysis","Power off the workstation immediately to \"freeze\" the evidence"],"answer":1,"explain":"Creating a forensically sound image under a documented chain of custody preserves evidentiary integrity and admissibility, even at the cost of 30 minutes, which is the correct trade-off for a potential legal matter. 'Open files directly on the live system immediately' can alter timestamps and metadata, undermining evidentiary value. 'Power off the workstation immediately' can destroy volatile memory evidence (such as running processes and encryption keys) that a proper live-response and imaging process would have captured."},{"label":"Why does chain of custody matter in this scenario?","hint":"Admissibility in potential legal proceedings","options":["It has no real impact on the outcome, it is just paperwork","It documents who handled the evidence and when, supporting admissibility if the case proceeds legally","It is only required for cases involving law enforcement"],"answer":1,"explain":"Chain of custody documents every person who handled the evidence and when, which is essential to demonstrating the evidence was not altered or tampered with if the matter proceeds to legal or disciplinary action. 'It has no real impact on the outcome, it is just paperwork' understates its role in evidentiary admissibility. 'It is only required for cases involving law enforcement' is incorrect; internal disciplinary and civil matters also benefit from and often require proper chain of custody."},{"label":"What volatile evidence risks being lost if the workstation is powered off immediately?","hint":"Memory-resident data disappears at shutdown","options":["Data stored permanently on the hard drive, which is lost on shutdown","Running processes, network connections, and encryption keys held in memory","Nothing; all evidence is safely preserved on disk regardless of power state"],"answer":1,"explain":"Volatile data such as running processes, active network connections, and in-memory encryption keys exists only while the system is powered on and is lost the moment it is shut down. 'Data stored permanently on the hard drive' is generally NOT lost on shutdown, which is why it is called non-volatile, unlike memory-resident evidence. 'Nothing; all evidence is safely preserved on disk regardless of power state' ignores the well-established loss of volatile memory evidence at shutdown."}]},
{"id":"PBQ-26","format":4,"domain":4,"obj":"4B1","title":"Communicating during a high-profile incident","brief":"A customer-impacting breach has become public on social media before the organization has issued any statement, and executives are asking how to respond.","exhibitTitle":"WORKPAPER — COMMUNICATIONS SITUATION","exhibit":"<span class='cy'>STATUS:</span> Breach confirmed internally 2 hours ago;\n  investigation ongoing; scope not yet fully determined.\n<span class='cy'>EXTERNAL SITUATION:</span> Rumors and speculation are\n  spreading rapidly on social media, some inaccurate.\n<span class='cy'>PROPOSED DRAFT STATEMENT:</span> Acknowledges an incident\n  is under investigation, states known facts only, and commits to\n  updates as more is confirmed.","fields":[{"label":"What is the BEST communications approach given the situation?","hint":"Timely, accurate, and expandable as facts emerge","options":["Issue no statement until the investigation is 100% complete, regardless of public speculation","Issue the proposed statement acknowledging the incident with known facts, avoiding speculation, and commit to timely updates","Issue a statement denying any incident occurred to calm the public"],"answer":1,"explain":"Given active public speculation, acknowledging the incident with only verified facts and committing to follow-up updates is the responsible approach that maintains credibility without overcommitting to unconfirmed details. 'Issue no statement until the investigation is 100% complete' cedes the narrative to inaccurate rumors for an indefinite period. 'Issue a statement denying any incident occurred' is dishonest and would cause severe credibility and legal damage once the truth emerges."},{"label":"Who should review the statement before it is released?","hint":"Coordinated, cross-functional sign-off","options":["The security manager alone, to move as fast as possible","Legal, communications/PR, and executive leadership, coordinated through the incident response plan's communication procedure","No one; social media speculation means speed matters more than accuracy"],"answer":1,"explain":"Public statements during an incident should be coordinated through legal, communications/PR, and executive leadership per the incident response plan, to ensure accuracy, legal defensibility, and consistent messaging. 'The security manager alone' lacks the legal and communications expertise to vet public statements safely. 'No one; social media speculation means speed matters more than accuracy' risks releasing an inaccurate or legally damaging statement under pressure."},{"label":"Why should the statement avoid speculating on scope before it is confirmed?","hint":"Premature claims can be wrong and damaging","options":["Because an inaccurate early claim about scope can require an embarrassing correction and damage credibility further","Because regulators forbid any public statement about breaches","Because the scope of a breach never changes once initially estimated"],"answer":0,"explain":"Speculating on scope before the investigation confirms it risks putting out an inaccurate figure that later must be corrected, compounding reputational damage. 'Because regulators forbid any public statement about breaches' is false; many regulators expect timely, appropriate communication. 'Because the scope of a breach never changes once initially estimated' is incorrect, initial scope estimates commonly change as an investigation progresses, which is exactly why premature specifics are risky."}]},
{"id":"PBQ-27","format":4,"domain":4,"obj":"4A4","title":"Testing the incident response plan","brief":"The incident response plan has not been tested in over a year, and the security manager must recommend a testing approach to the steering committee.","exhibitTitle":"WORKPAPER — IR TESTING OPTIONS","exhibit":"<span class='cy'>OPTION 1:</span> Tabletop exercise walking key stakeholders\n  through a simulated ransomware scenario and decision points.\n<span class='cy'>OPTION 2:</span> Full, unannounced live-fire simulation that\n  takes production systems offline without warning.\n<span class='cy'>OPTION 3:</span> No testing; simply re-read the plan document\n  annually.","fields":[{"label":"Which option is the MOST reasonable starting point for a plan untested in over a year?","hint":"Balance realism against operational risk","options":["Option 1 (tabletop exercise)","Option 2 (unannounced live-fire simulation)","Option 3 (re-read the document)"],"answer":0,"explain":"A tabletop exercise validates roles, decision points, and communication paths in a low-risk, controlled setting, making it the reasonable starting point for a plan that has gone untested for over a year. 'Option 2 (unannounced live-fire simulation)' is high-risk and could cause real business disruption before the plan's basic soundness has even been validated. 'Option 3 (no testing; simply re-read the document)' does not validate that people can actually execute the plan under pressure and provides no real assurance."},{"label":"What is a key risk of jumping straight to Option 2 without prior testing?","hint":"Untested plans plus live disruption is a dangerous combination","options":["It could cause real, unplanned business disruption while also exposing plan gaps that were never assessed in a controlled way first","It is guaranteed to be cheaper than a tabletop exercise","It requires no stakeholder participation at all"],"answer":0,"explain":"Running an unannounced live-fire test on an unvalidated plan risks compounding real operational disruption with the very plan gaps the test is meant to uncover, an unnecessarily high-risk approach for a first test. 'It is guaranteed to be cheaper than a tabletop exercise' is not a supported claim and live simulations are typically more resource-intensive. 'It requires no stakeholder participation at all' is false, a live simulation still requires broad participation, often under more stressful and less controlled conditions."},{"label":"After the tabletop exercise, what should happen with identified gaps?","hint":"Testing should drive improvement","options":["Document them and update the incident response plan and training accordingly","Ignore them since the exercise was only a simulation","Wait another year before addressing any gaps found"],"answer":0,"explain":"Gaps identified during a tabletop exercise should be documented and used to update the plan, procedures, and training, closing the loop between testing and improvement. 'Ignore them since the exercise was only a simulation' wastes the entire value of conducting the exercise. 'Wait another year before addressing any gaps found' unnecessarily delays fixing known weaknesses in the response capability."}]},
{"id":"PBQ-28","format":4,"domain":4,"obj":"4B6","title":"Determining root cause after service restoration","brief":"Systems have been restored after an incident, but the post-incident review must determine whether the true root cause was actually addressed.","exhibitTitle":"WORKPAPER — POST-INCIDENT FINDINGS","exhibit":"<span class='cy'>SYMPTOM:</span> Malware executed via a macro in an email\n  attachment that bypassed the email filter.\n<span class='cy'>SURFACE FIX APPLIED:</span> The specific malicious file hash\n  was blocked.\n<span class='cy'>UNDERLYING GAP (not yet addressed):</span> Macro execution\n  from email attachments is enabled by default organization-wide,\n  and the email filter's detection rules had not been updated in 8 months.","fields":[{"label":"Is blocking the specific file hash sufficient as a root-cause fix?","hint":"Symptom fix versus systemic fix","options":["Yes, because the exact malicious file can never be used again","No, because it addresses only this specific symptom, not the systemic macro and filter-maintenance gaps that allowed it","Yes, because file-hash blocking is the industry standard root-cause remedy"],"answer":1,"explain":"Blocking one file hash only stops that exact file; it does nothing about the systemic issues, default-enabled macros and a stale filter ruleset, that allowed the attack and will allow similar future attacks. 'Yes, because the exact malicious file can never be used again' is technically true but irrelevant, since attackers can trivially change the file to produce a new hash. 'Yes, because file-hash blocking is the industry standard root-cause remedy' mischaracterizes hash blocking as a root-cause fix when it is only a narrow, symptom-level control."},{"label":"What systemic changes should the post-incident review recommend?","hint":"Address both underlying gaps","options":["Disable macro execution from email attachments by default and establish a regular filter rule-update cadence","Only continue blocking new malicious file hashes as they are discovered","Disable the email system entirely to prevent any future attachments"],"answer":0,"explain":"Disabling macros from email attachments by default and instituting regular filter updates addresses both underlying systemic gaps identified in the review, not just the single symptom. 'Only continue blocking new malicious file hashes as they are discovered' is a reactive, incomplete measure that leaves the systemic gaps open. 'Disable the email system entirely' is a disproportionate response that would halt legitimate business communication."},{"label":"What does this scenario illustrate about the purpose of post-incident review?","hint":"Look past the immediate symptom","options":["Its purpose is solely to document who was on the response call","Its purpose is to identify and remediate the true underlying cause, not just the immediate symptom","Its purpose is to assign blame to whoever configured the email filter"],"answer":1,"explain":"Post-incident review exists to dig past the immediate symptom to the true underlying cause so systemic gaps are closed and recurrence is prevented, exactly as this scenario demonstrates. 'Its purpose is solely to document who was on the response call' reduces the review to administrative record-keeping, missing its improvement purpose. 'Its purpose is to assign blame to whoever configured the email filter' turns a learning process into a blame exercise, which discourages the open reporting a good post-incident culture depends on."}]},
{"id":"PBQ-29","format":4,"domain":4,"obj":"4A6","title":"Deciding when to engage external incident response support","brief":"An incident is escalating beyond the internal team's normal caseload and specialized skill set, and the security manager must decide whether to bring in outside help.","exhibitTitle":"WORKPAPER — ESCALATION DECISION","exhibit":"<span class='cy'>SITUATION:</span> Suspected nation-state-style intrusion with\n  advanced techniques the internal team has not handled before;\n  internal team is also fully occupied with normal operations.\n<span class='cy'>OPTION A:</span> Continue with internal team only, learning\n  the necessary forensic techniques as they go.\n<span class='cy'>OPTION B:</span> Engage a pre-vetted external incident response\n  retainer firm with the specialized skill set needed.","fields":[{"label":"Which option is the BEST course of action?","hint":"Match the response to the sophistication of the threat","options":["Option A","Option B","Neither; simply disconnect all systems from the network and wait"],"answer":1,"explain":"Engaging a pre-vetted external IR firm with the specialized skills needed for a sophisticated intrusion, while the internal team is already stretched, ensures the response matches the threat's sophistication without further delay. 'Option A' risks a slower, less thorough response while the internal team learns unfamiliar advanced techniques under pressure, and delays containment. 'Neither; simply disconnect all systems from the network and wait' is not a response, it avoids taking the necessary investigative and containment actions."},{"label":"Why does having a PRE-vetted retainer firm matter, rather than searching for one after the incident starts?","hint":"Time and trust are critical during an active incident","options":["It saves critical time and ensures contractual and trust groundwork is already in place when speed matters most","Pre-vetting has no real advantage over searching during the incident","Retainer firms are only useful for legal contract negotiation, not technical response"],"answer":0,"explain":"A pre-vetted retainer arrangement means contracts, NDAs, and working relationships are already established, so the firm can mobilize immediately rather than losing critical time to procurement and vetting during an active incident. 'Pre-vetting has no real advantage over searching during the incident' ignores the real time cost of vendor selection and contracting under pressure. 'Retainer firms are only useful for legal contract negotiation, not technical response' mischaracterizes their core purpose, which is specialized technical incident response."},{"label":"What should the internal team's role be once the external firm is engaged?","hint":"Collaboration, not full hand-off","options":["Step back entirely and have no further involvement in the incident","Continue providing environment knowledge, access, and coordination while the external firm supplies specialized expertise","Compete with the external firm to independently reach conclusions first"],"answer":1,"explain":"The internal team should continue supporting the effort with institutional and environment knowledge, access provisioning, and coordination, while the external firm contributes specialized forensic and response expertise, a collaborative model. 'Step back entirely and have no further involvement' wastes valuable internal context the external firm needs to work efficiently. 'Compete with the external firm to independently reach conclusions first' creates duplicated, uncoordinated effort and can slow the overall response."}]},
{"id":"PBQ-30","format":4,"domain":4,"obj":"4B8","title":"Closing the loop with lessons learned after a major incident","brief":"A major incident has been fully resolved, and the security manager must ensure the lessons-learned process produces real, lasting improvement.","exhibitTitle":"WORKPAPER — LESSONS-LEARNED PLANNING","exhibit":"<span class='cy'>PROPOSED APPROACH A:</span> Hold a blameless retrospective\n  with all responders, document findings, assign owners and\n  deadlines for corrective actions, and track them to closure.\n<span class='cy'>PROPOSED APPROACH B:</span> Write a short summary email\n  noting the incident is closed, with no further follow-up.","fields":[{"label":"Which approach will produce lasting improvement?","hint":"Accountability and tracking drive real change","options":["Approach A","Approach B","Neither; lessons-learned activities are optional once systems are restored"],"answer":0,"explain":"A blameless retrospective with documented findings, assigned owners, deadlines, and tracking to closure ensures identified gaps are actually remediated rather than forgotten. 'Approach B' provides closure notice but no mechanism to ensure any underlying gap is actually fixed. 'Neither; lessons-learned activities are optional once systems are restored' abandons a core part of incident management that prevents recurrence."},{"label":"Why does the retrospective need to be \"blameless\"?","hint":"Psychological safety drives honest input","options":["To encourage honest, complete input from responders without fear of punishment, surfacing the true root causes","Because no one actually made any mistakes during the incident","Because blame is legally prohibited in every jurisdiction"],"answer":0,"explain":"A blameless approach encourages responders to speak honestly about what happened, including their own missteps, which surfaces the true root causes rather than a sanitized version of events. 'Because no one actually made any mistakes during the incident' is an unfounded assumption; the point of blamelessness is to surface mistakes safely, not deny they occurred. 'Because blame is legally prohibited in every jurisdiction' is false and not the actual reason blameless retrospectives are used."},{"label":"What ensures the corrective actions from the retrospective are not forgotten?","hint":"Ownership and follow-through","options":["Assigning named owners and deadlines, then tracking each action item to closure","Trusting that everyone remembers the meeting discussion informally","Relying on the same summary email from Approach B"],"answer":0,"explain":"Assigning named owners and deadlines, and formally tracking each item until it is closed, is what prevents corrective actions from quietly falling through the cracks after the retrospective ends. 'Trusting that everyone remembers the meeting discussion informally' has no accountability mechanism and typically fails over time. 'Relying on the same summary email from Approach B' was already established as providing no follow-up mechanism at all."}]}

]);
